Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Trim, peel, and cut @carrots{9%ounce} on a diagonal into ½-inch-thick pieces. Halve, peel, and mince @shallot{1}; reserve half. Roughly chop @walnuts{½%ounce}.

Toss carrots on a #baking sheet{} with a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2.5%teaspoon}, half the @smoky cinnamon paprika spice{1%tablespoon} (you'll use more later), @salt{}, and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack until tender, ~{20-25%minutes}.

Meanwhile, heat a drizzle of oil in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add @Israeli couscous{2.5%ounce}, @golden raisins{1%ounce}, and half the shallot; cook, stirring, until couscous is lightly toasted and raisins and shallot are softened, ~{3-5%minutes}.

Add half the @chicken stock concentrate{2}, @water{¾%cup}; bring to a boil, then reduce to a low simmer and cover. Cook until couscous is tender, ~{6-8%minutes}. Keep covered off heat until ready to serve.

Pat @beef tenderloin steak{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{} and season all over with @garlic powder{1%teaspoon}, salt, and pepper.

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add beef and cook until browned and cooked through, ~{5-7%minutes} per side.

> TIP: If beef is on the thicker side, reduce heat to medium; cover and cook for 2-3 minutes more per side.

Transfer to a #cutting board{} to rest. Reserve pan.

> Swap in chicken or pork for beef; cook chicken until cooked through, 3-5 minutes per side, or cook pork to desired doneness, 4-7 minutes per side.

Heat a drizzle of oil in same pan over medium-high heat. Add remaining shallot, a pinch of salt, and pepper; cook, stirring occasionally, until fragrant and softened, ~{2-3%minutes}.

Stir in @water{½%cup}, @cranberry jam{1}, remaining stock concentrate, @smoky cinnamon paprika spice{1%teaspoon}, a pinch of salt, and pepper. Cook, stirring occasionally, until sauce begins to thicken, ~{3-5%minutes}.

> Be sure to measure the Cinnamon Paprika Spice—we sent more.

Remove from heat and stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} until melted. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

Stir walnuts into pot with couscous and season with salt and pepper to taste.

Slice beef crosswise.

> Slice chicken or pork against the grain.

Divide beef, couscous, and carrots between plates. Spoon sauce over beef and serve.

> Beef is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 145°.